text: Evo Morales, Bolivia's first Indigenous president and one of Latin America's most prominent leftists, has made a triumphant return to his home country after being controversially driven from power one year ago. https://t.co/C0U8smXPzX

name: NPR
text: Readers asked: Viruses weren’t typically considered preexisting condition. But COVID-19 isn’t your run-of-the-mill virus. https://t.co/7zBJP3hUyU

name: NPR
text:
Rabbi Jonathan Sacks, a celebrated moral thinker and globally renowned intellect of Judaism, died on Saturday at the age of 72.

"God is the god of all humanity," he famously wrote, "but no single faith is or should be the faith of all humanity."
https://t.co/pTEOmsU5uU

name: NPR
text:
Jigsaw puzzles have become such a favorite pandemic pastime, retailers are having a hard time keeping them in stock

"There's not a factory on the planet that is not months behind on production." says Brian Way, co-owner of Puzzle Warehouse. https://t.co/JmXPA6DlzO

name: NPR
text:
Mexican President Andrés Manuel López Obrador says he won't congratulate President-elect Joe Biden until U.S. authorities formally certify him as the winner.
https://t.co/bKfwfOTSAA

name: NPR
text:
Facebook has removed a network of pages linked to Steve Bannon that were spreading false claims and conspiracy theories about voter fraud to a collective following of more than 2.45 million people.
https://t.co/NZklNn34M7

name: NPR
text:
So far, only 4 GOP senators have broken party ranks to congratulate President-elect Biden: Susan Collins, Mitt Romney, Lisa Murkowski and Ben Sasse — all of whom have been critical of Trump in the past.
https://t.co/9SCzxireIL

name: NPR
text:
The head of the Justice Dept.'s election crimes branch has resigned over Attorney General Barr's memo authorizing prosecutors to investigate allegations of voting irregularities — which are baseless.

There has been no evidence of voting irregularities.
https://t.co/rFPrD83zUt

name: NPR
text:
Mariah Carey's new, long-awaited memoir — "The Meaning of Mariah Carey" — recounts a complicated childhood, challenging relationships and her career.

It's as detailed and entertaining as some of her best lyrics, critic Aisha Harris writes.
https://t.co/HIe3LLtJe6

name: NPR
text:
Singer Mickey Guyton has long been a favorite of country music connoisseurs for her lucid songwriting and dazzling vocal range. Now, she's claiming her place as a star for our times.

Watch her perform 3 songs for her Tiny Desk, including "Black Like Me."
https://t.co/AqT5DyHQ1l

name: NPR
text:
6 trans candidates were elected to state office this election cycle — including in Arkansas and Kansas. The total number of trans elected officials nationwide will jump from 28 to 32.
https://t.co/ErRnhCoar4

name: NPR
text:
Here are some of the biggest tech industry issues the Biden administration will start confronting in January:

⚫ U.S. v. Google
⚫ overhauling Section 230
⚫ online privacy
⚫ H-1B visas for immigrant workers
⚫ future of the gig economy
https://t.co/KIZq5dw2Sy

name: NPR
text: To American biologist Preston Estep, "warp speed" isn't fast enough. He and his team have been testing experimental COVID vaccines on themselves since March in an effort to move faster than the virus can. @WHYYThePulse https://t.co/bl9tyJTyJr

name: NPR
text:
Peru's legislature voted overwhelmingly last night to remove President Martín Vizcarra from office, condemning his handling of the pandemic and alleging he'd taken bribes while serving as a regional governor.
 https://t.co/zlqquURKgc

text: RT @nprpolitics: Georgia's two GOP senators, both of whom are heading to runoffs in January, issued a joint statement calling on the state's Republican elections chief to resign, claiming "failures" in the state's elections without any evidence to back up that claim. https://t.co/GyymhEH7T5

text:
